formattedAddress: 150 South Bridge Rd, Fook Hai Building

tip.text: The supreme example of Penang curry mee. Rich, flavourful broth. Cockles, thinly sliced char siew, tau pok, prawn, cuttlefish & blood cubes. You'll ask for seconds. But they'd have run out by 10.30am.

venue.name: Kedai Kopi Yit Hooi (逸园茶室)

tip.text: That squid ink pasta. Fresh, juicy, lemony and delicious from the first forkful to the very last sauce-soaked crumb of bread.
Generally too sweet across the range, the sugar is balanced against the bitterness in the beer sorbet. Great even on the coldest of autumn nights.
A bunch of good natured, oldish folk gathered around an extra-grand piano (sometimes spilling drinks all over it) as even older folk play hit classics, accompanied by vocalists. A Madrid must-do.
The best infused gin & tonics this side of Europe, expertly crafted, elegantly presented. Served to great atmosphere and music ranging from The Libertines to Morissey. Brilliant, brilliant.
Hawker cuisine's last great secret. For years it's been an unidentified stall parked under someone's zinc porch. Add pork ribs, lor & garlic paste for the ultimate expression of Penang Hokkien Mee.

If you don't come expecting thick, santan-laden curry with shredded chicken & cockles; you'll leave satisfied by the experience: old ladies, pots on the floor, cuttlefish, blood cubes & a light broth.

venue.name: Sister's Curry Mee (暹罗姐妹咖喱面)

tip.text: It looks like the best of Fallout 4 shack designs. It certainly serves some of the best food at un-apocalyptic prices. The red duck curry is fruity, complex and sublime. Friendly, earnest folk too.

Just up the road around a bend from the turnoff to Nook Dee & Foto Hotel, this road side stall offers a view of the sunset over Kata Noi and delicious, reasonably priced food to match. Worth the hike.
My rip-off cab fare from Kata Noi was three times the price of lunch, but it was definitely worth the trip. Chunky crab pieces in a robust yet nuanced curry lives up to most of the rave reviews.

venue.name: Kung Lee Sugar Cane Juice (公利真料竹蔗水)

tip.text: What used to be Methodist Boys' School's canteen is today a very pleasant place to ease airily from lunchtime to tea time, watching the teh-tarik coloured river bubble by across the lawn.
Great Michelin Bib Gourmand restaurant that doesn't intimidate. Our indecisive table of three tried the Chef's Choice and what followed was plate after plate of delightful little tweaks and treats.
The brilliantly hemispherical scoops are light & fluffy around the edges, cool & creamy at the core. Both a visual delight and a treat to the tongue. Takes ice cream beyond taste, into an experience.
A coffeeshop for both stars and discerning tourists. Great service if you're a noob, friendly staff and excellent range. Certainly better than the Bulldog joints. (Yes, in both senses of the word.)
Excellent, authentic south German fare, great host (Jorg) who's friendly, made 4/4 excellent beer recommendations. Wonderful neighbourhood, dodgy enough to add an edge of flavour while staying real.
If you're looking for a bite near Kinkaku-ji, this modest restaurant (with a garden-cum-smoking area tucked into the back) offers simple, very tasty fare. Try the cold tempura soba and unagi don.
I have nothing to compare Izuju's 100 year old recipe against, but the Inarizushi was a revelation. The sabazushi and hakozushi tasted as good as they looked. The sampling set is good value for two.

tip.text: Like coming home to grandma's house. They'd just closed when I stumbled into it. A brief, hushed discussion between two elderly ladies later, I was having the most authentic, homely higawari ever.

formattedAddress: 大阪材木町686-2 (姉小路堺町東入る)

tip.text: With walls that match the floor, and food that tastes like it's been scraped off either.

formattedAddress: #02-09, Funan DigitaLife Mall (109 North Bridge Rd.)

tip.text: Extremely flavourful and fulfilling. First time round, 3 out of 3 dishes excelled. Mutton curry, a spicy tomato purée and a mix of anchovy and shredded potato went perfectly with fragrant rice/naan.

"BKT" tastes so flat it'll make you see pigs on Xanax languidly backstroking across the surface without a care in the world. Also forget the "you tiao": thick, soggy chunks of dour, undercooked flour.

venue.name: Ya Hua Bak Kut Teh Eating House

tip.text: Lovely little airport. Compact, architecturally pleasing--inspired application of Khmer sensibilities in layout, pools and sculptures. Wonderful way to arrive in Siem Reap. Look up for Art Deco globe!

venue.name: Siem Reap International Airport (REP) (អាកាសយានដ្ឋានអន្តរជាតិសៀមរាប)

tip.text: You know how all food in Singapore is dire? Well, not quite! Hao Ji Fried Prawn Noodle (01-1108) doesn't just serve the best prawn noodly win, the char koay teow is rather Malaysian (KL-level) too!

formattedAddress: 32 New Market St (Eu Tong Sen St)

tip.text: From car seat to bar stool upholstery, Mr. Ooi does it all. Even custom requests - on the spot, with his bare hands. Decades ago he'd open till midnight - today he closes by 6pm, partly due to crime.
Queues are consistently two dozen people and that number of centuries long. There's a fruit juice stall along the line to stave off inevitable mummification.

tip.text: Replaces District 10 as my neighbourhood rendezvous. Beautifully done up, properly prepared food, great skyving hour deals on the wine; the only blemish being badly conceived copy on the placemats.
Nice traditional sarongs in silk and cotton. Prices can be bargained down by at least 20-30%, maybe more but I'm not the sort that enjoys haggling.
